          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
        Central Asia alienated
       </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>Summary: Despite Central Asia‚Äôs long-standing relations with Russia, China is gaining in the area.</strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Russia‚Äôs longstanding dominance in Central Asia is waning. After President Putin's pivot away from Europe toward the "East," Russia hoped to strengthen its role in Central Asia. However, recent developments, including the Valdai Club‚Äôs conference, <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-14-may-25-analysis-h1-5-revealed-a-shift-in-mood" target="_blank">revealed a shift in mood</a>. While Russian speakers prioritized ideological narratives, Central Asian delegates focused on economic growth and cooperation.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Countries like Tajikistan and Uzbekistan emphasized job creation and monetary backing, while others called for reduced reliance on Moscow. Russia‚Äôs mistreatment of Central Asian migrants and recent arrests of Kyrgyz nationals involved in Russian military recruitment have caused diplomatic friction.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Sanctions on Russia have unexpectedly helped Central Asian economies. These nations function as trade intermediaries and build their monetary systems. While Russia still maintains influence through the Eurasian Economic Union and Collective Security Treaty Organization, China‚Äôs military and economic influence is growing.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
      Central Asia is increasingly pursuing a "multi-vector" foreign policy, balancing relations with China and the West. Trade with Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan jumped over 30% in 2023. Beijing is Uzbekistan's top trading partner. China is also enhancing its security role, especially in Tajikistan.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
